This paper is likely to belong to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category as it focuses on detecting and mining anomalous traffic, which is a crucial aspect of network security. The use of Deep Learning techniques such as Bidirectional Long Short-Term Memory (Bi-LSTM) and attention mechanism also suggests that it could belong to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories. The paper's emphasis on enhancing the generalization capabilities of the model by integrating structural information and incrementally updating the data set also suggests that it could belong to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on HTTP traffic, which is a common protocol used in web applications, suggests that it could belong to the cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) sub-category.
